      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Construct stiffness QoI comparison — non-cannulated 7.5 mm",
      "description": "Detailed comparison of FEA-predicted construct stiffness against N=11 experimental measurements pooled from two independent laboratories (FDA CDRH and DePuy Synthes). The FEA ensemble mean stiffness was 187.4 N/mm versus an experimental mean of 183.1 N/mm (2.3% difference). The validation metric E/uval = 0.74, well below the acceptance threshold of 1.96. Both laboratories independently confirmed convergence of the FEA solution under identical boundary conditions: distal vertebral body block rigidly constrained, superior block loaded at 10 mm/min quasi-static displacement rate per ASTM F1717-15. Mesh sensitivity analysis confirmed <1.2% change in predicted stiffness between medium and fine mesh densities (1.1 M vs 2.4 M elements). Material properties for Ti-6Al-4V rod and screw were assigned from ASTM F136 coupon data supplied by the manufacturer; UHMWPE block modulus was measured at 0.93 GPa via three-point bending. The simulation was executed in Ansys Mechanical 2021 R2 on an FDA-managed HPC cluster. This result constitutes the primary evidence for construct stiffness credibility and was reviewed and accepted by the multi-disciplinary assessment team at the conclusion of the validation study. All raw force-displacement traces, FEA output decks, and post-processing scripts are archived in the FDA CDRH shared repository under accession NAG-COU1-2023-STIFF.",
